              <h2>What is the heat index?</h2>
              <p>
                The <strong>heat index</strong> (also called
                <strong>apparent temperature</strong> or “<em>feels like</em>”
                temperature) combines <strong>air temperature</strong> and
                <strong>relative humidity</strong> to estimate how hot it feels
                to the human body. High humidity reduces the evaporation of
                sweat, making it harder for your body to cool itself.
              </p>
              <p>
                For example, an air temperature of <strong>90 °F</strong> (32
                °C) with <strong>70% humidity</strong> can feel like
                <strong>105–110 °F</strong> (40–43 °C) to your body.
              </p>

              <h2>Heat index formula (NOAA)</h2>
              <p>
                The calculator uses the widely accepted
                <strong
                  >NOAA/National Weather Service regression formula</strong
                >
                for heat index in degrees Fahrenheit:
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p class="font-mono">
                  HI = −42.379 + 2.04901523·T + 10.14333127·RH − 0.22475541·T·RH
                  − 0.00683783·T² − 0.05481717·RH²<br />
                  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;+ 0.00122874·T²·RH + 0.00085282·T·RH²
                  − 0.00000199·T²·RH²
                </p>
                <ul class="mt-2 list-disc ml-5">
                  <li><strong>T</strong> = air temperature in °F</li>
                  <li><strong>RH</strong> = relative humidity in % (0–100)</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <p>
                This equation is valid primarily for
                <strong>T ≥ 80 °F</strong> (27 °C) and
                <strong>RH ≥ 40%</strong>. Outside this range, the heat index is
                usually close to the actual air temperature, and the calculator
                smoothly transitions toward T.
              </p>

              <h3>Adjustments for very low or very high humidity</h3>
              <p>
                NOAA applies small corrections in some extreme humidity
                situations. This tool includes those adjustments:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong
                    >Very low humidity (RH &lt; 13%) and hot (80–112 °F)</strong
                  >
                  – heat index is adjusted slightly <em>downward</em>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong
                    >Very high humidity (RH &gt; 85%) and warm (80–87
                    °F)</strong
                  >
                  – heat index is adjusted slightly <em>upward</em>.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>How to use the heat index calculator</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Choose the <strong>temperature unit</strong> (°F or °C).
                </li>
                <li>Enter the current <strong>air temperature</strong>.</li>
                <li>
                  Enter the <strong>relative humidity</strong> (from your
                  weather app, station, or hygrometer).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Click <strong>Calculate</strong> to see:
                  <ul>
                    <li>Heat index in °F and °C</li>
                    <li>Color-coded <strong>risk level</strong></li>
                    <li>
                      Short <strong>safety guidance</strong> based on your
                      result
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Practical safety tips for high heat index</h2>
              <p>
                <strong
                  >Always follow local public health and weather authority
                  guidance.</strong
                >
                In general:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Hydrate</strong> regularly, even if you don’t feel
                  thirsty.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Avoid strenuous activity</strong> during the hottest
                  part of the day.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Wear
                  <strong
                    >lightweight, light-colored, loose-fitting clothing</strong
                  >.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Use <strong>air conditioning</strong> or visit cooling centers
                  if available.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Never leave
                  <strong>children, pets, or vulnerable adults</strong> in
                  parked vehicles.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Check on <strong>older adults</strong> and people with chronic
                  conditions.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Limitations of the heat index</h2>
              <p>
                The heat index is a useful guideline, but it has limitations:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Assumes <strong>shade</strong> and
                  <strong>light wind</strong>. Direct sun can add 10–15 °F (6–8
                  °C) or more.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Does not account for <strong>wind speed</strong>,
                  <strong>clothing</strong>, or <strong>activity level</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Does not replace medical advice. If someone shows signs of
                  heat illness (confusion, fainting, no sweating, very hot
                  skin), seek <strong>emergency care immediately</strong>.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>Is heat index the same as “feels like” temperature?</h3>
              <p>
                Many weather services use heat index as the basis for “feels
                like” temperature in hot conditions. Some providers may also
                factor in wind, sun, and other variables, so their “feels like”
                value can differ slightly.
              </p>

              <h3>What heat index is considered dangerous?</h3>
              <p>
                According to NOAA, heat index values above
                <strong>103 °F (39 °C)</strong> fall into the
                <strong>Danger</strong> category, where heat cramps and heat
                exhaustion are likely and heat stroke is possible. Above
                <strong>125 °F (51 °C)</strong>, heat stroke is highly likely
                with prolonged exposure or physical activity.
              </p>

              <h3>Why does high humidity make it feel hotter?</h3>
              <p>
                Your body cools itself mainly by
                <strong>evaporating sweat</strong>. When the air is very humid,
                sweat evaporates more slowly, so your body retains more heat.
                The heat index captures this effect by combining temperature and
                humidity into a single number.
              </p>
